<chapter xml:id="chapter-linear-dynamical-systems" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Linear Dynamical Systems</title>
  <section xml:id="section-linear-dynamical-systems">
      <title>Linear dynamical systems</title>
      <p>
        A quantity that evolves over time in discrete steps can often be represented or approximated using linear models:
        <me>\xx_{k+1} = A\xx_k</me>.
        One important example is the <em>Markov model</em>.
        If <m>\xx_0</m> is the initial configuration of the system, then after <m>k</m> steps the system will have configuration
        <me>\xx_k = A^k\xx_0</me>.
      </p>
      <subsection xml:id="subsection-markov-models">
        <title>Markov models</title>
        <p>
          A <em>Markov model</em> is a probabilistic model for how a system evolves over time.
          In such a model we can be in one of several given states at any step <m>k</m>.
          The <em>transition matrix</em> <m>A</m> describes the likelihood of the system evolving from one state to another.
        </p>
        <p>
          For instance, suppose we wish to model the weather in Buckhannon in June.
          Reasonable states for the weather are sunny <m>(S)</m>, cloudy <m>(C)</m> and rainy <m>(R)</m>.
          Suppose that
          <md>
            <mrow>P_{S\to S} \amp = 0.3, P_{S\to C} \amp = 0.3 P_{S\to R} \amp = 0.4</mrow>
            <mrow>P_{C\to S} \amp = 0.15, P_{C\to C} \amp = 0.3 P_{C\to R} \amp = 0.55</mrow>
            <mrow>P_{R\to S} \amp = 0.2, P_{R\to C} \amp = 0.5 P_{R\to R} \amp = 0.3</mrow>
          </md>.
          We also know that on June 1 there is a <m>65\%</m> chance of sunshine and a <m>35\%</m> chance of cloudy weather.
          The probability that it will be sunny on June 2 is given by
          <me>.65P_{S\to S} + .35_{C\to S} + 0P_{R\to S} = 0.2475</me>.
          Likewise, the probabilities that it will be cloudy or rainy are given by
          <md>
            <mrow>.65P_{S\to C} + .35P_{C\to C} + 0P_{R\to C} \amp = 0.3</mrow>
            <mrow>.65P_{S\to R} + .35P_{C\to R} + 0P_{R\to R} \amp = 0.4525</mrow>
          </md>.
        </p>
        <p>
          We can rewrite these computations as the matrix equation
          <me>\xx_1 = A\xx_0</me>
          where
          <me>\xx_0 = \mqty[0.65\\0.35\\0], \xx_1 = \mqty[0.2475 \\ 0.3 \\ 0.4525]</me>
          and
          <me>A = \mqty[P_{S\to S} \amp P_{C\to S} \amp P_{R\to S} \\ P_{S\to C} \amp P_{C\to C} \amp P_{R\to C} \\ P_{S\to R} \amp P_{C\to R} \amp P_{R\to R}] = \mqty[0.3 \amp 0.15 \amp 0.2 \\ 0.3 \amp 0.3 \amp 0.5 \\ 0.4 \amp 0.55 \amp 0.3]</me>.
        </p>
      </subsection>
  </section>
